<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Henry, Alexander. Travels in the Red River Department (Abridged), 1806. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0024</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p><span class="fw">45</span>
</p>
<p>N<sup>o</sup> 12</p>
<p><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p>July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Bulls heads.  To each of these heads three Yards of cord are fixed which cord is passed and tied to an incision made in the penitents shoulders who in this manner walks round the Village with eight or nine Bulls heads trailling after him and often getting entangled by the horns into pits and other obstructions which happen to be in the way when children who follow in crowds upon such <span class="AddHand-author">serious</span> occasions make it their business to assist the sufferer out of such dificulties<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  For as many days as he was absent so many heads <span class="AddHand-author">he</span> drags and so many round<span class="AddHand-author">s</span> he makes of the village &#8212; and sometimes they suffer so much pain as to become almost senseless<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[W]</span>hen the rounds are completed his friends disengage him from his troubles applauding his fortitude and courage while they conduct him to his own tent often in a shocking condition so much so that many of these poor fellows languish for months before they recover<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">These Indians have another method of trying the courage of the Young people this is done by pinching the skin and flesh an</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">(inch)</p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[49]</span></p>

